                    <div class="modal-body">
                        <p>Waking up feeling refreshed is the key to having a good day. The best way to accomplish that is to wake up at a time where you're not disrupting your own sleepcycle. A sleep cycle calculator like this works by timing the average cycle and applying it several times to offer different wake-up times, so you can wake up at just the right time!<img class="modal-img" src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/f750a5b7f2ba7d473a7324189bea6266/d3865c33e28835bd-f5/s1280x1920/49dec66e38d705f49dde22dcaa84e317a46fe6d4.pnj" height="250" width="250">
                        <h4>There are four stages to a sleep cycle. Usually, a person goes through 4-6 sleep cycles a night.</h4>
                        <img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/208eca0def148b4f55c78afc2c0bfe63/bd9723b3e47c3305-c1/s1280x1920/d6eb921fd5c65459679515380fa8a4ce3286c18c.pnj" height="13" width="340">
                        <p>The first three stages are known as NREM ‚Äî Non Rapid Eye Movement. The higher the stage of NREM sleep, the harder it is to wake up!</p>
                        <p><strong><span style="color: #e685ac">Stage 1</span></strong>, also known as N1, typically lasts for 1-7 minutes. This is basically when you're falling asleep.</p>
                        <p><strong><span style="color: #e685ac">Stage 2</span></strong>, N2, lasts a bit longer, for 10-25 minutes. Your body is more subdued in this stage.</p>
                        <p><strong><span style="color: #e685ac">Stage 3</span></strong> has a few more names. N3, slow-wave sleep, delta sleep, or deep sleep. This stage lasts for 20-40 minutes. It's hard to wake someone up during this stage, and this stage is theorized to be critical to restorative sleep. It's important!</p>
                        <p>As you continue sleeping, these three initial stages actually get shorter in length and we start to spend more time in stage 4.</p>
                        <p><strong><span style="color: #e685ac">Stage 4</span></strong> is when we finally reach REM sleep, which stands for Rapid Eye Movement. This stage lasts for 10-60 minutes. In this stage, your eyes are moving, well, rapidly. Your brain activity picks up, and you can get some pretty vivid dreams.</p>
                        If you want to know more, check out <a href="https://www.cci.health.wa.gov.au/~/media/CCI/Mental-Health-Professionals/Sleep/Sleep---Information-Sheets/Sleep-Information-Sheet---01---Facts-About-Sleep.pdf">this handout by the Centre for Clinical Interventions</a>, and sleep well! ‚ú®üõèÔ∏èüí§ </p>
